hands_on_practices.solution:
1. The rate of change of core mass is 
$$\frac{dM_c}{dt}=\frac{L}{\epsilon_H\,X_s}.$$
2. The luminosity is $L=f(M_c)$, so 
$$\frac{dL}{dt}=f'(M_c)\,\frac{dM_c}{dt}
=f'(M_c)\,\frac{L}{\epsilon_H\,X_s}.$$
3. Just before the bump (pre), $M_c=M_D$, $L=L_{pre}$, $X_s=X_{pre}$, giving 
$$\biggl(\frac{dL}{dt}\biggr)_{pre}
=\frac{f'(M_D)\,L_{pre}}{\epsilon_H\,X_{pre}}.$$
4. At the luminosity minimum (post), $M_c=M_D$, $L=L_{post}$, $X_s=X_{post}$, so 
$$\biggl(\frac{dL}{dt}\biggr)_{post}
=\frac{f'(M_D)\,L_{post}}{\epsilon_H\,X_{post}}.$$
5. The evolutionary timescale $\tau\propto(dL/dt)^{-1}$, hence
$$\frac{\tau_{post}}{\tau_{pre}}
=\frac{(dL/dt)_{pre}}{(dL/dt)_{post}}
=\frac{\displaystyle\frac{f'(M_D)\,L_{pre}}{\epsilon_H\,X_{pre}}}
{\displaystyle\frac{f'(M_D)\,L_{post}}{\epsilon_H\,X_{post}}}
=\frac{L_{pre}\,X_{post}}{L_{post}\,X_{pre}}.$$
